citeinfo.title: Buildings Marinette County, WI 2017

descript.abstract: This point data layer represents buildings for Marinette County, Wisconsin in 2017. [The Structural Zone Map provides structural mapping and predefined compartments or zones for the Towns of Amberg, Athelstane, Beaver, Beecher, Dunbar, Goodman, Niagara, Pembine, Silver Cliff, Stephenson and Wausaukee, and the Village of Crivitz, all located in Marinette County, Wisconsin. These compartments were created to coordinate the emergency efforts in order to ensure emergency services are not duplicated or areas are not omitted from coverage. This document was created and the data compiled by the Marinette County Land Information Department in the spring of 2005 with the assistance from the Wisconsin Department of Natural Resources. Updates were completed in 2007 and 2009. Project funding was received from the State of Wisconsin Department of Natural Resources Division of Forestry. For more information contact the Marinette County Land Information Department at (715) 732-7535.]

procstep.procdesc:
The strucaddzone.mdb is a personal geodatabase containing four feature classes. 1) bldgsite - Point feature class representing a "structure point". There is one point per parcel regardless of the number of buildings (DNR requirement). 2) site - Annotation feature class representing a "fire number". 3) zone_name - Annotation feature class for the name of the zone. 4) zones - Polygon feature class designating an area as a zone.
The bldgsite feature class was created utilizing a couple of AML's. Marinette County tax roll information was combined with the ACAD parcel mapping data to create a temporary coverage dataset. Parcels with improvement values were selected and the nodes were converted to a features class. Ortho photography was used to verify and to help position the point at the building location. The attribute table contains a method of placement field and a reliability field.
The site feature class was created at the same time as the bldgsite verification and placement. The source of the information was the Marinette County tax roll. Efforts were made to check and verify problems areas but not all data was field checked. Resolution of problem areas will be an ongoing process between the county and the towns.
The bldgsite information was then given to the DNR and staff created and named the zones. The corresponding zones were digitzed by the county and the zone_name annotation feature class was created. Working copies of the data were then reviewed and checked by the county and DNR staff.
The final product includes a 42-page booklet titled "Marinette County Structural Zone Map 2005". Copies of the book were given to the DNR for distribution.
